post_text:
The National Association of Elementary School Principals is committed to preparing assistant principals to step into the principal role. Recognition for the exceptional leadership of the men and women who are responsible for the day-to-day operations of PreK-8 schools instills pride in their accomplishments and reinforces their leadership in helping children develop a lifelong love of learning. The Mississippi Association of Elementary School Principals has awarded Mrs. Amy Cobb with the Mississippi Outstanding Assistant Principal of the Year Award. Mrs. Cobb is beginning her 21st year as an educator in DeSoto County. This will be her third year serving as the Assistant Principal at Walls Elementary School. She is married to Jay and they have two boys, David and Brayden.
Pictured (left to right): Supt. Cory Uselton, WES Principal Erica Armstrong, Mrs. Cobb, and Amanda Samples, Executive Director of Academic Support and School Improvement
#TeamDCS

post_text:
Southaven High School Graduate Attending Harvard in the Fall

Southaven High School 2020 graduate, Mia Word, will further her education at Harvard University in Cambridge, Massachusetts. Mia earned an ACT score of 31 and graduated with a GPA of 4.7. Mia plans to major in English and political science. Mia attended a summer program at Harvard when she was 16-years-old. The program gave her the vision to apply for Ivy League schools. Mia chose Harvard because of the university‚Äôs diversity. She added that the school reflects the population and socioeconomics of America. Mia‚Äôs inspiration comes from her mom, Rolonda Brown. She has been with Mia every step of the way. #TeamDCS

post_text:
LHS Graduate, Khilan Walker, is on his way to Duke University.

Lewisburg High School 2020 graduate, Khilan Walker, is on his way to Duke University in North Carolina. Khilan scored a 34 on his ACT and graduated with a GPA of 4.56. He plans to major in public policy and engineering. Khilan chose Duke University because he believes the school is the total package and has strong programs for first-year students. Khilan credits his mom and grandmother for giving him courage to apply to Duke. He recognizes the two women have a strong work ethic and impeccable faith. Khilan has further inspiration by the work-based mission trips he took to Miami and the Dominican Republic while he was in high school. Khilan says he has courage because of his family and faith. His parents are Teela Walker and Keith Patton. #TeamDCS

post_text:
HHS Graduate Heads to Vanderbilt University

Kaelyn Fann, daughter of Art and Holly Fann, is a Hernando High School graduate of 2020. Kaelyn has big plans for the next step of her education. She is headed to Vanderbilt University to major in biomedical engineering. Kaelyn said she chose Vanderbilt University because it has community-based value academics, social aspects, and a great location. The school feels secluded, but is in the heart of the city of Nashville. Kaelyn would like to work with new technologies. She credits Hernando High teachers, Ms. Floate, Ms. Trapolino, and Ms. Neel. All three of these HHS teachers gave her the confidence to look at selective schools. #TeamDCS

shared_text:
Mayor Musselwhite
May 7 at 5:37 PM ¬∑

2020 SENIORS‚Ä¶

Congratulations! I know this is not how you always envisioned your last weeks in school and I‚Äôm sorry this has happened, but I hope I can encourage you today.

Life is full of disappointments, but they all pale to the victories, happiness, and successes that lie ahead.

This will not be the worst thing that ever happens to you, but life is not about what happens to you, but instead, how you respond to what happens to you.

The pages of life do not turn smoothly like a storybook, but the pen to write your story is always in your hand and the future‚Äôs pages are always as white as snow.

Look how far you‚Äôve come and never forget the confidence you‚Äôve built or the lessons you‚Äôve learned, but listen to me, you‚Äôve only just begun.

Wishing you all the best,

Mayor Darren Musselwhite

#youwillriseabove #youveonlyjustbegun

The pages of life do not turn smoothly like a storybook, but the pen to write your story is always in your hand and the future‚Äôs pages are always as white as snow.

Look how far you‚Äôve come and never forget the confidence you‚Äôve built or the lessons you‚Äôve learned, but listen to me, you‚Äôve only just begun.

Wishing you all the best,

Mayor Darren Musselwhite

#youwillriseabove #youveonlyjustbegun

shared_text:
Cory Uselton
March 16 at 2:21 AM ¬∑

Email sent to DeSoto County Schools parents.....
Dear Parents: In a news report from Action News 5 today, their reporter misunderstood a situation involving the 180-day requirement for schools in Mississippi. The report stated "He (Uselton) is hoping the district will get a waiver to delay school 180 days." The correct information is that Mr. Uselton hopes to receive a waiver so that students do not have to meet the 180-day requirement for the 2019-2020 school year. If districts receive the waiver, this would relieve students from having to make up missed days from this week. Mr. Uselton does not want parents to get confused with the incorrect report. Thank you.

post_text: Overpark Elementary raised $12,564 for the St. Jude Math-a-Thon this year. OES has raised more than $200,000 since 2007. Paola Plascencia of St. Jude accepted the check from top student fundraisers. Kevin Medlin of Bankplus generously donated two wagons, and Mr. Uselton was present to encourage the little Mustangs. OES 5th grader Olivia Springer and her mom Holly Springer celebrate OES‚Äô accomplishment. Livy is one of the top fundraisers and a St. Jude success story. She was diagnosed with malignant melanoma at age three. Thanks to treatment at St. Jude, she will celebrate seven years cancer free this fall. #TeamDCS #RaiseTheBar
